. This colonial reality generated a distinctive vision of just warfare and political community. Working across the fields of Hispanic literature, the history of political thought, and studies of empire, colonialism and globalisation, Choi reinterprets three major works of colonial Latin American literature: Alonso de Ercilla's La Araucana (1569-90), Pedro de Oña's Arauco domado (1596), and Juan de Miramontes Zuázola's Armas antárticas (1608-9). She argues that these works provide a rare insight into the development of political thought in Viceregal Peru. Through the imaginative mirrors of epic, the reader is forced to ask the same questions of the unfinished conquests of the Americas as of those in Africa, Asia or Europe: when conflicting forces are divided by irreconcilable world views, even if the war is won, how is it possible to achieve peace?  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEpic poetry, SpanishxHistory and criticism. 0aPolitics in literature. 0aSpanish American poetryyTo 1800xHistory and criticism. 0aWar in literature. 4aEarly Modern Literature. 4aHispanic Studies. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Caribbean & Latin American.2bisacsh  aAfrica.  aAlonso de Ercilla.  aAmericas.  aAmerindian Republics.  aArauco domado.  aArmas antárticas.  aAsia.  aColonial Peru.  aColonial Reality.  aColonialism.  aConflict Ethics.  aConquests.  aEmpire.  aEpic Mirror.  aEthical Solutions.  aEurope.  aGlobalization.  aHispanic Literature.  aHistory of Political Thought.  aIrreconcilable World Views.  aJuan de Miramontes Zuázola.  aJust Warfare.  aLa Araucana.  aLiterature.  aMaroon Kingdoms.  aPeace.  aPedro de Oña.  aPoetry.  aPolitical Communities.  aPolitical Community.  aSearch for Solutions.  aSeventeenth Century.  aSixteenth Century.  aSpanish Empire.  a